  {
    "type": "EXEGETICAL (ORIGINAL LANGUAGES)",
    "name": "Pulpit Commentary",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "cmt_sub_title",
        "text": "Verse 5.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " - ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "cmt_word",
        "text": "The images",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "; Hebrew, ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "hebrew",
        "text": "חַמָּנֹים",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". The ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "accented",
        "text": "images",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " spoken of here are, of coarse, not the same with those (noted upon already) of ver. 3. The present ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "accented",
        "text": "khammanim are",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " mentioned seven times beside, viz. ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Leviticus 26:30",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "; ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "2 Chronicles 34:4, 7",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "; ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Isaiah 17:8",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "; ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Isaiah 27:9",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "; ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Ezekiel 6:4, 6",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". Gesenius says ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "accented",
        "text": "Khamman",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " is an epithet of Baal as bearing rule over the sun (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "hebrew",
        "text": "חַמָה",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", \"heat,\" or \"the sun\"), in the oft-found compound expression, ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "hebrew",
        "text": "בַֹּעַל חַמָּן",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "; he thinks the plural (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "hebrew",
        "text": "חַמָּנִים",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "), invariably found in the Old Testament, is short for ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "hebrew",
        "text": "בְּעָלִים חַמָּנִים",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". He does not agree with the translation of Haenaker ('Miscell. Phoen.,' p. 50), \"sun-image\" by aid of the word ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "hebrew",
        "text": "פֶסֶל",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " understood, images said to have been of a pyramid form, and placed in the most sacred positions of Baal-temples. This, however, is the rendering adopted by not a few modern commentators (so ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "2 Chronicles 34:4",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "). Gesenius would render \"the Sun-Bard,\" or \"the Sun-Lord,\" ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "accented",
        "text": "i.e.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " statues of the sun, representing a deity to whom (see ' Phoen. Inseript.') votive stones,were inscribed. In his 'Thesaurus' (p. 489) Gesenius instances the Phoenician inscriptions, as showing that ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "accented",
        "text": "our chemmanim",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " denoted statues of both Baal, the sun-god, and Astarte, the moon-goddess. 2 Chronicles 14:5",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "",
        "children": []
      }
    ]
  },
  {
    "type": "EXEGETICAL (ORIGINAL LANGUAGES)",
    "name": "Keil and Delitzsch Biblical Commentary on the Old Testament",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "He removed from all the cities of Judah the altars of the high places, and the חמּנים, sun-pillars, pillars or statues consecrated to Baal as sun-god, which were erected near or upon the altars of Baal (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "2 Chronicles 34:4",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "; see on ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Leviticus 26:30",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "). In consequence of this the kingdom had rest לפניו, before him, i.e., under his oversight (cf. ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Numbers 8:22",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "). This ten-years' quiet (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "2 Chronicles 14:1",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ") which God granted him, Asa employed in building fortresses in Judah (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "2 Chronicles 14:5",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "). \"We will build these cities, and surround them with walls and towers, gates and bolts.\" It is not said what the cities were, but they were at any rate others than Geba and Mizpah, which he caused to be built after the war with Baasha (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "2 Chronicles 16:6",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "). \"The land is still before us,\" i.e., open, free from enemies, so that we may freely move about, and build therein according to our pleasure. For the phraseology, cf. ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Genesis 13:9",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". The repetition of דּרשׁנוּ, ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "2 Chronicles 14:6",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", is impassioned speech. \"They built and had success;\" they built with effect, without meeting with any hindrances.",
        "children": []
      }
    ]
  }
]